                    <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                      <tr align="left" valign="top"> 
                        <td> 
                          <p class="headings">10/16/00: Not an RPG by <a href="mailto:phrost@rpgplanet.com">Phrost</a></p>
                          <p><span class="news">There’s been a lot of discussion 
                            lately about Verant’s recent ban of a player who wrote 
                            a controversial story and posted it to an EverQuest 
                            fan site.&nbsp; But so far, just about everyone who’s 
                            objected to it has failed to take into account one 
                            simple fact.&nbsp; The banning of Myztere isn’t about 
                            intellectual property rights, obscenity, or even about 
                            a conflict or personal tastes.&nbsp; While I do agree 
                            with most of the arguments people have put up against 
                            his banning (torturing a level 14 Dark Elf is worse 
                            than killing a pregnant Halfling I guess) all of these 
                            arguments are pointless once you realize what the 
                            truth of the matter is.&nbsp; “What truth is that 
                            Meesta Phrosty?”&nbsp; Simple:<o:p> </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">EverQuest is not a roleplaying 
                            game.<o:p> </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">Now take a deep breath, blink 
                            a few times, and wipe off the Mountain Dew you just 
                            spit all over your monitor… and read further.<o:p> 
                            </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">Once upon a time there was a man 
                            named Gary Gygax.&nbsp; Gary had a vision (not “The 
                            Vision™) of what a roleplaying game should be.&nbsp; 
                            He filled his world with heroes and monsters and villains.&nbsp; 
                            Unfortunately for Gary and his company, TSR, his game 
                            took off in that hyper-religious period of time we 
                            call “The 80’s”.&nbsp; Reagan was president, Nancy 
                            said no to drugs, Tipper was banning Heavy Metal, 
                            Tammy Faye was painting her face like a circus clown, 
                            and imagination was the enemy of the establishment. 
                            (Who needs kids who dream? They won’t grow up and 
                            be proper little wage slaves!)&nbsp; <o:p> </o:p> 
                            </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">Accusations of satanic heresies 
                            (the first refuge of the ignorant) abounded.&nbsp; 
                            Dungeons and Dragons was blamed for everything from 
                            suicide to teenage pregnancy and the deficit.&nbsp; 
                            You see, in the 80’s, much like it is today, many 
                            parents paid little attention to their children due 
                            to a pursuit of material wealth. So a scapegoat was 
                            needed for the parents to blame when their children 
                            “went bad” due to this neglect.&nbsp; Heavy Metal 
                            was one of these scapegoats, and so was D&amp;D.&nbsp; 
                            <o:p> </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">Why D&amp;D?&nbsp; Well one of 
                            the rulebooks, the Monstrous Manual included (gasp) 
                            demons, which as we all know are bad, mmkay?&nbsp; 
                            That made them a prime target for the moral crusaders 
                            who were looking to “protect” America from anything 
                            they thought was “naughty”. God forbid that young 
                            adults be exposed to a fantasy evil that they would 
                            adventure together in order to defeat.<o:p> </o:p> 
                            </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">Fast-Forward to the present day, 
                            to EverQuest, and the land of Norrath.&nbsp; Norrath, 
                            you see, is much like a fudge-covered Oreo™ cookie: 
                            Dark on the outside, with corpses hanging from hooks, 
                            torture racks, and blood stains on walls, but wholesome 
                            in the middle because everyone is expected to be friendly 
                            to each other, regardless of their race’s “history”.<o:p> 
                            </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">About a year ago, my little inky 
                            Necro was the terror of Nektulos forest.&nbsp; I was 
                            a fledgling lord of the shadows.&nbsp; I summoned 
                            undead to serve the will of the Prince of Hate.&nbsp; 
                            I called upon powerful magics in order to further 
                            his power.&nbsp; I laughed as my enemies died at my 
                            feet, begging for my help… only to be told:<o:p> </o:p> 
                            </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">&nbsp;“Dood, u r a dick”.<o:p> 
                            </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">My guild, the Disciples of Innoruuk, 
                            was the terror of the server and rightly so for we 
                            followed the will of Hatred. We mocked the petty, 
                            inferior races for their weak adherence to “good”.&nbsp; 
                            Our sorcerers would make our Ogres and Trolls invisible 
                            to trap enemies in the tiny dungeon corridors with 
                            vicious monsters. We took what we wanted to, not caring 
                            for anyone who stood in our way… only to be told:<o:p> 
                            </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">&nbsp;“Dood, u guys are dicks”.<o:p> 
                            </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">Our small band that served the 
                            god of Hate persevered in the face of overwhelming 
                            odds.&nbsp; Almost no one would ally with us, much 
                            less provide our members any assistance if we were 
                            in need.&nbsp; In fact, when the more powerful guilds 
                            were reaping the treasured Rubicite Armor from the 
                            bowels of the lost temple of Cazic Thule (*cough* 
                            Farming *cough*) we were forced to overcome our foes 
                            through skullduggery to acquire it… only to be told 
                            by Verant’s GM’s:<o:p> </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">&nbsp;“Dood, u guys have to stop 
                            being dicks or you will be banned”.<o:p> </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">Apparently Verant had come up 
                            with an idea for everyone to “Play Nice”, and this 
                            meant that there was no place in their world for a 
                            band of murdering Ogres, man-eating Trolls, or manipulative 
                            Dark Elves.<o:p> </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">It also meant that there was no 
                            place for anyone that truly roleplayed.<o:p> </o:p> 
                            </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">Somewhere in the recent past, 
                            the words “fantasy” and “roleplaying” became interchangeable.&nbsp; 
                            Game companies market new “RPG’s” all the time, but 
                            are they really roleplaying games? Do you really get 
                            to “chose” a role in Final Fantasy 7?&nbsp; Are you 
                            free to take whatever course of action you chose in 
                            Baldur’s Gate?&nbsp; The answer to both, for the most 
                            part, is no. EverQuest is a prime example of this.&nbsp; 
                            It’s not an RPG.&nbsp; It’s a fantasy version of Quake 
                            with server-stored, semi-permanent characters.&nbsp; 
                            Although as a result of the interaction with other 
                            people in the game you’re allowed a great deal more 
                            freedom than in Final Fantasy, you’re still not allowed 
                            to truly deal with that snotty High Elf the way an 
                            Ogre would in D&amp;D.&nbsp; The game was never designed 
                            to be anything other than Player vs. Environment… 
                            and that means it’s not a roleplaying game.<o:p> </o:p> 
                            </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">So if you look at the banning 
                            of Myztere through this set of eyes you can understand 
                            why Verant took the course of action that it did.&nbsp; 
                            EverQuest isn’t Dungeons and Dragons.&nbsp; EverQuest 
                            will be gone in a few years, replaced by something 
                            better.&nbsp; In the meantime, when it comes down 
                            to a choice between banning a roleplayer and keeping 
                            the moral crusaders off their backs (and out of their 
                            pocketbooks), and risking an association with “evil” 
                            like D&amp;D that could shorten EQ’s already limited 
                            lifespan…<o:p> </o:p> </span></p>
                          <p><span class="news">…what would you expect them to 
                            do?&nbsp; It’s not really a roleplaying game anyway.&nbsp; 
                            Ask Gary Gygax.<o:p> </span> 
                          <p class="news" align="center"><a href="http://www.eqcorner.com/forums/topic.asp?topic_id=28807&amp;forum_id=1315&amp;Topic_Title=Comments%3A+%28PHOF%29+%2D+Not+an+RPG&amp;forum_title=EQ+Tavern&amp;M=0&amp;S=True" target="_blank">Comments? 
                            Post your comments to Phrost in our Forums.</a> 
                          <p align="center"> 
                        </td>
